00:48:03.420 --> 00:48:05.010
leader or something like that.

00:48:05.010 --> 00:48:13.030
It's a natural affinity of
people that have really just

00:48:13.030 --> 00:48:14.550
had this intention.

00:48:14.550 --> 00:48:16.650
We were sort of,
like, going around,

00:48:16.650 --> 00:48:18.730
looking for other people
who had this intention

00:48:18.730 --> 00:48:21.170
to live-- not on a commune.

00:48:21.170 --> 00:48:22.870
We actually don't
live communally.

00:48:22.870 --> 00:48:27.480
There's a few group
homes-- in a community.

00:48:27.480 --> 00:48:31.240
Or more than community-- what
we're talking about-- tribe.

00:48:31.240 --> 00:48:37.539
So it looks like
there's a consistency.

00:48:37.539 --> 00:48:39.080
It's the first time
I've really felt,

00:48:39.080 --> 00:48:43.890
in my life, this sort of
consistency of people who

00:48:43.890 --> 00:48:49.830
care about me, who intend for
me to do better in my life,

00:48:49.830 --> 00:48:51.990
and I intend for them.

00:48:51.990 --> 00:48:55.970
And it was cultivated
relatively intentionally.

00:48:55.970 --> 00:48:59.150
And maybe you can talk about
how it gets cultivated?

00:48:59.150 --> 00:49:00.670
BRYAN FRANKLIN: Yeah.

00:49:00.670 --> 00:49:04.260
I also want to just
note that there

00:49:04.260 --> 00:49:08.770
are those in the tribe who
earn less than $30,000 a year.

00:49:08.770 --> 00:49:12.440
And there are those in the tribe
who have a net worth in excess

00:49:12.440 --> 00:49:13.330
of $100 million.

00:49:13.330 --> 00:49:16.180
So it's quite a range.

00:49:16.180 --> 00:49:20.350
And the how is it
begins, really,

00:49:20.350 --> 00:49:24.190
with a soul search for you,
of what you care most about.

00:49:28.760 --> 00:49:30.790
Imagine looking
back on your life,

00:49:30.790 --> 00:49:34.600
and asking yourself
in what way did

00:49:34.600 --> 00:49:37.900
you want to change
other people's

00:49:37.900 --> 00:49:41.960
experiences for the better.

00:49:41.960 --> 00:49:43.674
And if you look
at the work you do

00:49:43.674 --> 00:49:45.090
and the way you
like to socialize,

00:49:45.090 --> 00:49:47.530
and kind of relationships
you like to have,

00:49:47.530 --> 00:49:49.290
the times when
you have felt most

00:49:49.290 --> 00:49:53.880
fulfilled probably correlate
to other people being

00:49:53.880 --> 00:49:56.510
benefited in a specific way.

00:49:56.510 --> 00:49:59.520
And so I would
begin by identifying

00:49:59.520 --> 00:50:03.540
what that is, and then start to
talk with my existing friends

00:50:03.540 --> 00:50:06.220
about that specific benefit.

00:50:06.220 --> 00:50:07.990
Like, hey, I notice
that I really

00:50:07.990 --> 00:50:11.170
care about people feeling this
way or having this experience,

00:50:11.170 --> 00:50:13.380
or being benefited
in a specific way.

00:50:13.380 --> 00:50:17.090
And naturally, because they're
your friends, some of them

00:50:17.090 --> 00:50:19.551
will share this value.

00:50:19.551 --> 00:50:21.800
And then I would start just
getting together with them

00:50:21.800 --> 00:50:24.700
and having dinner parties
and having the question--

00:50:24.700 --> 00:50:30.420
what do you suppose we
could do together somewhere

00:50:30.420 --> 00:50:33.560
in the two-hour-a-week
kind of time commitment,

00:50:33.560 --> 00:50:36.300
or one hour a week, what do you
think that we could do together

00:50:36.300 --> 00:50:38.100
that would maximize that impact?

00:50:38.100 --> 00:50:40.350
Or maximize our
individual ability

00:50:40.350 --> 00:50:42.880
to have that impact
in our lives?

00:50:42.880 --> 00:50:46.430
And just start having the
question be in the friendships

00:50:46.430 --> 00:50:47.670
that you have.

00:50:47.670 --> 00:50:53.561
And that is the
nucleus of a tribe.

00:50:53.561 --> 00:50:55.810
Once you start asking that
and answering that together

00:50:55.810 --> 00:50:58.560
and discovering it
together, then you

00:50:58.560 --> 00:51:01.200
start to gain understandings
and technologies

00:51:01.200 --> 00:51:05.560
for how you can collaborate
inside of a work environment,

00:51:05.560 --> 00:51:08.930
outside a work environment,
to have that impact.

00:51:08.930 --> 00:51:11.586
AUDIENCE: So the short answer
is make your own tribe?

00:51:11.586 --> 00:51:12.460
BRYAN FRANKLIN: Yeah.

00:51:12.460 --> 00:51:13.900
Yeah, I mean, I
would start that.

00:51:13.900 --> 00:51:16.490
And then what will
happen as you do that,

00:51:16.490 --> 00:51:19.750
is you'll start to notice
other existing tribes that are

00:51:19.750 --> 00:51:21.430
currently not on your radar.

00:51:21.430 --> 00:51:24.580
And then you might glob onto
one or be adopted by one

00:51:24.580 --> 00:51:25.700
or join one.

00:51:25.700 --> 00:51:28.174
That has happened
as well, with us.

00:51:28.174 --> 00:51:29.590
AUDIENCE: I think
it's interesting

00:51:29.590 --> 00:51:34.070
that what seems like
almost just life advice,

00:51:34.070 --> 00:51:39.000
you're putting it in a form
of investment advice, which

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:41.250
is a neat twist.

00:51:41.250 --> 00:51:44.020
But taking that
as an approach, I

00:51:44.020 --> 00:51:47.590
think about a lot
of your advice seems

00:51:47.590 --> 00:51:52.330
like it's further investment
in your one big investment,

00:51:52.330 --> 00:51:54.950
which is yourself.

00:51:54.950 --> 00:51:57.520
A lot of times, people think
about traditional financial

00:51:57.520 --> 00:52:00.790
investing as a way
of diversifying over

00:52:00.790 --> 00:52:03.590
their complete investment in
their own skills and abilities

00:52:03.590 --> 00:52:07.170
so that they don't--
maybe someday,

00:52:07.170 --> 00:52:10.300
if they lose some of those
skills and abilities,

00:52:10.300 --> 00:52:12.340
they'll still be able
to eat and have shelter.

00:52:12.340 --> 00:52:16.140
So what do you think about
the diversification question?

00:52:16.140 --> 00:52:19.480
BRYAN FRANKLIN: Yeah,
so first of all,

00:52:19.480 --> 00:52:24.520
I don't think we can
diversify, other than ourself.

00:52:24.520 --> 00:52:28.760
I think we have
the one unit here.

00:52:28.760 --> 00:52:33.750
And the way that the principle
of diversification to me

00:52:33.750 --> 00:52:37.970
applies to this life
advice, is to invest

00:52:37.970 --> 00:52:42.380
in the kinds of relationships
and the kinds of skills

00:52:42.380 --> 00:52:47.540
that are valuable in the
most diverse situations.

00:52:47.540 --> 00:52:51.370
In terms of there's
this idea of retirement,

00:52:51.370 --> 00:52:54.030
or when I want to
stop adding value

00:52:54.030 --> 00:52:56.650
but want to still
be getting value.

00:52:56.650 --> 00:53:00.690
And the way that we address
that in the book, in the plan,

00:53:00.690 --> 00:53:07.500
is to look at the idea of
advisor equity, or how can

00:53:07.500 --> 00:53:11.370
you start to have the
kinds of contributions

00:53:11.370 --> 00:53:16.960
that you make be divorced from
the time you spend making them?

00:53:16.960 --> 00:53:19.040
Which is a rather
advanced concept.

00:53:19.040 --> 00:53:26.810
But if you're invested in say,
a tribe of 150 people, which

00:53:26.810 --> 00:53:30.130
are diverse people,
and you're continually

00:53:30.130 --> 00:53:35.420
building positive capital
with them, then more and more,

00:53:35.420 --> 00:53:40.870
their success can be a part of
your future financial success.

00:53:40.870 --> 00:53:46.120
And we can all share,
basically, our future benefit.

00:53:46.120 --> 00:53:49.110
The more the tribe starts
to span generations,

00:53:49.110 --> 00:53:51.500
the more the elder
generation is taken care

00:53:51.500 --> 00:53:56.130
of by the generation that
is in their working prime.

00:53:56.130 --> 00:53:58.380
MICHAEL ELLSBERG: One thing
I would add to that, also,

00:53:58.380 --> 00:54:02.570
on this question
of diversification,

00:54:02.570 --> 00:54:08.030
is our belief is that you
should not be risking money just

00:54:08.030 --> 00:54:09.110
to get more money.

00:54:09.110 --> 00:54:12.420
So basically, everyone
needs savings.

00:54:12.420 --> 00:54:15.370
We need savings, perhaps
a lot of savings,

00:54:15.370 --> 00:54:17.830
to weather different
storms, or to retire, to not

00:54:17.830 --> 00:54:19.270
have to work for some period.

00:54:19.270 --> 00:54:21.700
But in our opinion, that
should really be savings.

00:54:21.700 --> 00:54:23.770
Like, a lot of people
think when they put money

00:54:23.770 --> 00:54:26.210
in a 401K, that's savings.

00:54:26.210 --> 00:54:26.940
No, it's not.

00:54:26.940 --> 00:54:27.920
That's investing.

00:54:27.920 --> 00:54:28.630
That's risking.

00:54:28.630 --> 00:54:31.170
I mean, people saw just
how much that was risking.

00:54:31.170 --> 00:54:32.420
Same thing with the home.

00:54:32.420 --> 00:54:33.860
Home equity is not savings.

00:54:33.860 --> 00:54:37.920
It's an investment that is
taking a lot of risk, actually.

00:54:37.920 --> 00:54:42.660
And we saw the risk,
again, about 10 years ago.

00:54:42.660 --> 00:54:49.540
In my opinion, the ways
we should risk our money

00:54:49.540 --> 00:54:53.050
involve doing things
where it's a project where

00:54:53.050 --> 00:54:55.230
money isn't the only thing
we're going to get back.

00:54:55.230 --> 00:54:59.630
And there's some value actually
occurring in the risk itself,

00:54:59.630 --> 00:55:04.040
that there's some experiential
value in the risk.

00:55:04.040 --> 00:55:07.490
Take, say, an example
from my own life.

00:55:07.490 --> 00:55:08.770
I'm a writer.

00:55:08.770 --> 00:55:12.360
I just spent-- invested--
six months of my time

00:55:12.360 --> 00:55:18.690
and quite a bit of money getting
a manuscript ready for an agent

00:55:18.690 --> 00:55:20.660
and possible publication.

00:55:20.660 --> 00:55:22.287
It didn't end up working out.

00:55:22.287 --> 00:55:23.620
I won't go into all the details.

00:55:23.620 --> 00:55:27.080
But basically, nothing
came of that six months.

00:55:27.080 --> 00:55:31.007
Now, had that been purely me
spending that time or the time

00:55:31.007 --> 00:55:32.840
value of the money and
putting it in a stock

00:55:32.840 --> 00:55:36.485
and then the stock went to zero,
I'd be pretty pissed about it

00:55:36.485 --> 00:55:37.490
and pretty bummed.

00:55:37.490 --> 00:55:40.106
But actually, I was
able to learn things

00:55:40.106 --> 00:55:40.980
from this experience.

00:55:40.980 --> 00:55:42.240
I was able to get ideas.

00:55:42.240 --> 00:55:45.750
I was able to come away from
it feeling like, OK, well, it

00:55:45.750 --> 00:55:47.410
didn't turn out
the way I wanted.

00:55:47.410 --> 00:55:48.940
But I actually
learned something.

00:55:48.940 --> 00:55:50.840
And now I'm going to
go in this direction.

00:55:50.840 --> 00:55:54.410
So that has this sort of
experiential quality, where

00:55:54.410 --> 00:55:57.760
the money being
invested was tied up

00:55:57.760 --> 00:56:01.090
in things that had a
tie to my life narrative

00:56:01.090 --> 00:56:05.230
in such a way that the
risk almost wasn't a risk.

00:56:05.230 --> 00:56:06.782
It was just part
of doing the things

00:56:06.782 --> 00:56:08.740
that I wanted to do in
life and learning, which

00:56:08.740 --> 00:56:10.390
is what we all do.

00:56:10.390 --> 00:56:14.490
So yeah, diversification of some
things that are really, really,

00:56:14.490 --> 00:56:16.010
really low risk.

00:56:16.010 --> 00:56:17.620
And then the things
that are higher

00:56:17.620 --> 00:56:21.580
risk are tied up in
the things you actually

00:56:21.580 --> 00:56:23.230
care about and the
kind of narrative

00:56:23.230 --> 00:56:25.920
that you're building
of your life story.

00:56:25.920 --> 00:56:29.400
BRYAN FRANKLIN: I also
want to point out that it's

00:56:29.400 --> 00:56:30.670
an important economic theory.

00:56:30.670 --> 00:56:32.560
It's an important
investment theory.

00:56:32.560 --> 00:56:36.770
But it actually hasn't worked
out for the average person.

00:56:36.770 --> 00:56:40.890
98% of baby boomers
say, they don't

00:56:40.890 --> 00:56:43.640
have enough money to retire.

00:56:43.640 --> 00:56:47.780
So it hasn't worked,
is the problem.

00:56:47.780 --> 00:56:48.280
You know?

00:56:48.280 --> 00:56:52.920
If the existing
advice was working,

00:56:52.920 --> 00:56:55.120
then I think we
probably wouldn't

00:56:55.120 --> 00:56:57.500
have written that book.

00:56:57.500 --> 00:57:02.590
And the theory of
diversification, again,

00:57:02.590 --> 00:57:08.010
for it to take hold, requires
a massive education investment

00:57:08.010 --> 00:57:11.020
in investing in that
particular asset class,

00:57:11.020 --> 00:57:14.760
to learn what is actually
diversified and what isn't.

00:57:14.760 --> 00:57:16.644
So it just reminded
me of that part.

00:57:16.644 --> 00:57:18.060
AUDIENCE: I was
just wondering how

00:57:18.060 --> 00:57:21.180
you reconcile-- my mom was a
public school teacher growing

00:57:21.180 --> 00:57:21.680
up.

00:57:21.680 --> 00:57:23.910
So it was all about
not being in a clique.

00:57:23.910 --> 00:57:25.670
And kids would be
like, be in my crew.

00:57:25.670 --> 00:57:26.620
I like you.

00:57:26.620 --> 00:57:30.070
And I have been following her
advice through high school,

00:57:30.070 --> 00:57:31.830
college, business school, etc.

00:57:31.830 --> 00:57:34.310
And so when I get approached,
be in my lean-in circle,

00:57:34.310 --> 00:57:37.040
or be in my crew, or we're
a clique, we're the girls,

00:57:37.040 --> 00:57:40.310
we're the Plastics, whatever
it may be, great pitch, right?

00:57:40.310 --> 00:57:43.190
I've been declining on purpose
and following my parents'

00:57:43.190 --> 00:57:46.530
advice not to be part
of a said tribe, where

00:57:46.530 --> 00:57:50.470
there are a distinct number
of people in a group.

00:57:50.470 --> 00:57:53.960
So how do reconcile that
advice and your own,

00:57:53.960 --> 00:57:56.170
to try to create a tribe?

00:57:56.170 --> 00:57:57.990
BRYAN FRANKLIN: Sure.

00:57:57.990 --> 00:58:01.450
So the first is that the cliques
that you were told not to join

00:58:01.450 --> 00:58:05.000
had, as a primary value,
exclusion of others.

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:07.920
That was, like, their number
one deal, was to exclude others.

00:58:07.920 --> 00:58:10.600
And for any tribe
to be healthy, it

00:58:10.600 --> 00:58:12.590
has to have porous boundaries.

00:58:12.590 --> 00:58:16.980
People have to be able to join
and leave as it suits them,

00:58:16.980 --> 00:58:18.920
without much drama.

00:58:18.920 --> 00:58:22.310
And the way that you
would join our tribe

00:58:22.310 --> 00:58:26.080
is if you had the same values
and you started to hang out.

00:58:26.080 --> 00:58:28.390
Or you knew someone, you
got invited to an event,

00:58:28.390 --> 00:58:29.470
and then you were
at the event, you

00:58:29.470 --> 00:58:30.719
wanted to come to another one.

00:58:30.719 --> 00:58:31.680
And you were there.

00:58:31.680 --> 00:58:33.179
If you were there
more often, you're

00:58:33.179 --> 00:58:36.010
going to be in, provided
that you are actually

00:58:36.010 --> 00:58:38.020
living in accordance to
the values of service

00:58:38.020 --> 00:58:42.450
and contribution, of freedom,
of devotion, and of growth.

00:58:42.450 --> 00:58:48.070
So I think the difference
between a healthy tribe

00:58:48.070 --> 00:58:50.690
and an unhealthy
clique, or even a cult,

00:58:50.690 --> 00:58:52.760
is the values that
it's centered around.

00:58:52.760 --> 00:58:56.340
And they have to really
resonate as your values.

00:58:56.340 --> 00:58:58.276
So that's the first
thing I'd say.

00:58:58.276 --> 00:59:00.150
MICHAEL ELLSBERG: What
does Jennifer call it?

00:59:00.150 --> 00:59:02.445
Like, a duocracy or something?

00:59:02.445 --> 00:59:03.820
BRYAN FRANKLIN:
Oh, effortocracy.

00:59:03.820 --> 00:59:05.361
MICHAEL ELLSBERG:
Yeah, effortocracy.

00:59:05.361 --> 00:59:09.080
Like, the cliques
you're talking about,

00:59:09.080 --> 00:59:12.090
it's about prestige and who's
cool, and who's not cool.

00:59:12.090 --> 00:59:17.240
And better metric,
we think, is a tribe

00:59:17.240 --> 00:59:20.000
that basically people
who are doing the most

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:23.589
to create the events or make
things happen for people,

00:59:23.589 --> 00:59:25.380
or support each other,
they're the ones who

00:59:25.380 --> 00:59:28.740
are kind of rising
naturally to leadership.

00:59:28.740 --> 00:59:31.700
So it's almost like an
effortocracy, rather than

00:59:31.700 --> 00:59:34.640
a cool-ocracy.

00:59:34.640 --> 00:59:35.840
Thank you for having us.

00:59:35.840 --> 00:59:37.816
Thank you for taking an
hour out of your day.

